6. Operational Models:
{
    "6. Operational Models": [
        {
            "Original": "This section describes some of the current most common DHCP operational models.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The described models are not mutually exclusive and are sometimes used together.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, a device may start in stateful mode to obtain an address and, at a later time when an application is started, request additional parameters using stateless mode.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This document assumes that the DHCP servers and the client, communicating with the servers via a specific interface, belong to a single provisioning domain.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP may be extended to support additional stateful services that may interact with one or more of the models described below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Such interaction should be considered and documented as part of any future protocol extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

5. Client/Server Exchanges:
{
    "5. Client/Server Exchanges": [
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers exchange DHCP messages using UDP (see [RFC768] and BCP 145 [RFC8085]).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client uses a link-local address or addresses determined through other mechanisms for transmitting and receiving DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP client sends most messages using a reserved, link-scoped multicast destination address so that the client need not be configured with the address or addresses of DHCP servers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To allow a DHCP client to send a message to a DHCP server that is not attached to the same link, a DHCP relay agent on the client's link will relay messages between the client and server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The operation of the relay agent is transparent to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The discussion of message exchanges in the remainder of this section will omit the description of the relaying of messages by relay agents.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Once the client has determined the address of a server, it may, under some circumstances, send messages directly to the server using unicast.",
            "Adjusted": "Once the client has determined the address of a server, the client may, under some circumstances, send messages directly to the server using unicast."
        }
    ]
}

14. Transmission of Messages by a Client:
{
    "14. Transmission of Messages by a Client": [
        {
            "Original": "Unless otherwise specified in this document or in a document that describes how IPv6 is carried over a specific type of link (for link types that do not support multicast), a client sends DHCP messages to the All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers multicast address.",
            "Adjusted": "Unless otherwise specified in this document or in a document that describes how IPv6 is carried over a specific type of link for link types that do not support multicast, a client sends DHCP messages to the All DHCP Relay Agents and Servers multicast address."
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP servers SHOULD NOT check to see whether the Layer 2 address used was multicast or not, as long as the Layer 3 address was correct.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client uses multicast to reach all servers or an individual server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "An individual server is indicated by specifying that server's DUID in a Server Identifier option (seeSection 21.3) in the client's message.",
            "Adjusted": "An individual server is indicated by specifying that server's DUID in a Server Identifier option (see Section 21.3) in the client's message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "(All servers will receive this message, but only the indicated server will respond.) All servers are indicated when this option is not supplied.",
            "Adjusted": "All servers will receive this message, but only the indicated server will respond. All servers are indicated when the Server Identifier option is not supplied."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client may send some messages directly to a server using unicast, as described in Section 21.12.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

20. Authentication of DHCP Messages:
{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "This document introduces two security mechanisms for the authentication of DHCP messages: (1) authentication (and encryption) of messages sent between servers and relay agents using IPsec and (2) protection against misconfiguration of a client caused by a Reconfigure message sent by a malicious DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The delayed authentication protocol, defined in [RFC3315\"\")], has been obsoleted by this document (see Section 25).",
            "Adjusted": "The delayed authentication protocol, defined in RFC3315, has been obsoleted by this document (see Section 25)."
        }
    ]
}

19. Relay Agent Behavior:
{
    "19. Relay Agent Behavior": [
        {
            "Original": "The relay agent SHOULD be configured to use a list of destination addresses that includes unicast addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The list of destination addresses MAY include the All_DHCP_Servers multicast address or other addresses selected by the network administrator.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the relay agent has not been explicitly configured, it MUST use the All_DHCP_Servers multicast address as the default.",
            "Adjusted": "If the relay agent has not been explicitly configured, the relay agent MUST use the All_DHCP_Servers multicast address as the default."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the relay agent relays messages to the All_DHCP_Servers multicast address or other multicast addresses, it sets the Hop Limit field to 8.",
            "Adjusted": "If the relay agent relays messages to the All_DHCP_Servers multicast address or other multicast addresses, the relay agent sets the Hop Limit field to 8."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the relay agent receives a message other than Relay-forward and Relay-reply and the relay agent does not recognize its message type, it MUST forward the message as described inSection 19.1.1.",
            "Adjusted": "If the relay agent receives a message other than Relay-forward and Relay-reply and the relay agent does not recognize the message type, the relay agent MUST forward the message as described in Section 19.1.1."
        }
    ]
}

12. Identity Association:
{
    "12. Identity Association": [
        {
            "Original": "An Identity Association (IA) is a construct through which a server and a client can identify, group, and manage a set of related IPv6 addresses or delegated prefixes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each IA consists of an IAID and associated configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The IAID uniquely identifies the IA and MUST be chosen to be unique among the IAIDs for that IA type on the client (e.g., an IA_NA with an IAID of 0 and an IA_PD with an IAID of 0 are each considered unique).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The IAID is chosen by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For any given use of an IA by the client, the IAID for that IA MUST be consistent across restarts of the DHCP client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may maintain consistency by either storing the IAID in non-volatile storage or using an algorithm that will consistently produce the same IAID as long as the configuration of the client has not changed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "There may be no way for a client to maintain consistency of the IAIDs if it does not have non-volatile storage and the client's hardware configuration changes.",
            "Adjusted": "There may be no way for a client to maintain consistency of the IAIDs if the client does not have non-volatile storage and the client's hardware configuration changes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client uses only one IAID, it can use a well-known value, e.g., zero.",
            "Adjusted": "If the client uses only one IAID, the client can use a well-known value, e.g., zero."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client wishes to obtain a distinctly new address or prefix and deprecate the existing one, the client sends a Release message to the server for the IAs using the original IAID.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client then creates a new IAID, to be used in future messages to obtain leases for the new IA.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

16. Message Validation:
{
    "16. Message Validation": [
        {
            "Original": "This section describes which options are valid in which kinds of message types and explains what to do when a client or server receives a message that contains known options that are invalid for that message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, an IA option is not allowed to appear in an Information-request message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers MAY choose to either (1) extract information from such a message if the information is of use to the recipient or (2) ignore such a message completely and just discard it.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a server receives a message that it considers invalid, it MAY send a Reply message (or Advertise message, as appropriate) with a Server Identifier option (seeSection 21.3), a Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) (if one was included in the message), and a Status Code option (see Section 21.13) with status UnspecFail.",
            "Adjusted": "If a server receives a message that it considers invalid, the server MAY send a Reply message (or Advertise message, as appropriate) with a Server Identifier option (see Section 21.3), a Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) (if one was included in the message), and a Status Code option (see Section 21.13) with status UnspecFail."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients, relay agents, and servers MUST NOT discard messages that contain unknown options (or instances of vendor options with unknown enterprise-number values).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "These should be ignored as if they were not present.",
            "Adjusted": "Unknown options should be ignored as if they were not present."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is critical to provide for future extensions of DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "Ignoring unknown options is critical to provide for future extensions of DHCP."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A server MUST discard any Solicit, Confirm, Rebind, or Information-request messages it receives with a Layer 3 unicast destination address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client or server MUST discard any received DHCP messages with an unknown message type.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

