21. DHCP Options:
{
    "21. DHCP Options": [
        {
            "Original": "Options are used to carry additional information and parameters in DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Every option shares a common base format, as described inSection 21.1.",
            "Adjusted": "Every option shares a common base format, as described in Section 21.1."
        },
        {
            "Original": "All values in options are represented in network byte order.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This document describes the DHCP options defined as part of the base DHCP specification.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Other options may be defined in the future in separate documents.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "See [RFC7227] for guidelines regarding the definition of new options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "See Section 24 for additional information about the DHCPv6 \"Option Codes\" registry maintained by IANA.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Unless otherwise noted, each option may appear only in the options area of a DHCP message and may appear only once.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If an option does appear multiple times, each instance is considered separate and the data areas of the options MUST NOT be concatenated or otherwise combined.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Options that are allowed to appear only once are called \"singleton options\".",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The only non-singleton options defined in this document are the IA_NA (see Section 21.4), IA_TA (see Section 21.5), Vendor Class (see Section 21.16), Vendor-specific Information (see Section 21.17), and IA_PD (see Section 21.21) options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, IA Address (see Section 21.6) and IA Prefix (see Section 21.22) may appear in their respective IA options more than once.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

11. DHCP Unique Identifier (DUID):
{
    "11. DHCP Unique Identifier (DUID)": [
        {
            "Original": "Each DHCP client and server has a DUID.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP servers use DUIDs to identify clients for the selection of configuration parameters and in the association of IAs with clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP clients use DUIDs to identify a server in messages where a server needs to be identified.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "See Sections21.2 and 21.3 for details regarding the representation of a DUID in a DHCP message.",
            "Adjusted": "See Sections 21.2 and 21.3 for details regarding the representation of a DUID in a DHCP message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers MUST treat DUIDs as opaque values and MUST only compare DUIDs for equality.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers SHOULD NOT in any other way interpret DUIDs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers MUST NOT restrict DUIDs to the types defined in this document, as additional DUID types may be defined in the future.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It should be noted that an attempt to parse a DUID to obtain a client's link-layer address is unreliable, as there is no guarantee that the client is still using the same link-layer address as when it generated its DUID.",
            "Adjusted": "An attempt to parse a DUID to obtain a client's link-layer address is unreliable, as there is no guarantee that the client is still using the same link-layer address as when the client generated its DUID."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, such an attempt will be more and more unreliable as more clients adopt privacy measures such as those defined in [RFC7844].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this capability is required, it is recommended to rely on the Client Link-Layer Address option instead [RFC6939].",
            "Adjusted": "If the capability to obtain a client's link-layer address is required, it is recommended to rely on the Client Link-Layer Address option instead [RFC6939]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The DUID is carried in an option because it may be variable in length and because it is not required in all DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The DUID is designed to be unique across all DHCP clients and servers, and stable for any specific client or server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "That is, the DUID used by a client or server SHOULD NOT change over time if at all possible; for example, a device's DUID should not change as a result of a change in the device's network hardware or changes to virtual interfaces (e.g., logical PPP (over Ethernet) interfaces that may come and go in Customer Premises Equipment routers).",
            "Adjusted": "The DUID used by a client or server SHOULD NOT change over time if at all possible; for example, a device's DUID should not change as a result of a change in the device's network hardware or changes to virtual interfaces (e.g., logical PPP (over Ethernet) interfaces that may come and go in Customer Premises Equipment routers)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may change its DUID as specified in [RFC7844].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The motivation for having more than one type of DUID is that the DUID must be globally unique and must also be easy to generate.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The sort of globally unique identifier that is easy to generate for any given device can differ quite widely.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, some devices may not contain any persistent storage.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Retaining a generated DUID in such a device is not possible, so the DUID scheme must accommodate such devices.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

15. Reliability of Client-Initiated Mess:
{
    "15. Reliability of Client-Initiated Message Exchanges": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP clients are responsible for reliable delivery of messages in the client-initiated message exchanges described inSection 18.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP clients are responsible for reliable delivery of messages in the client-initiated message exchanges described in Section 18."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a DHCP client fails to receive an expected response from a server, the client must retransmit its message according to the retransmission strategy described in this section.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that the procedure described in this section is slightly modified when used with the Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The modified procedure is described in Section 18.2.1.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client begins the message exchange by transmitting a message to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The message exchange terminates when either (1) the client successfully receives the appropriate response or responses from a server or servers or (2) the message exchange is considered to have failed according to the retransmission mechanism described below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST update an \"elapsed-time\" value within an Elapsed Time option (see Section 21.9) in the retransmitted message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In some cases, the client may also need to modify values in IA Address options (see Section 21.6) or IA Prefix options (see Section 21.22) if a valid lifetime for any of the client's leases expires before retransmission.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Thus, whenever this document refers to a \"retransmission\" of a client's message, it refers to both modifying the original message and sending this new message instance to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client retransmission behavior is controlled and described by the following variables: RT Retransmission timeout IRT Initial retransmission time MRC Maximum retransmission count MRT Maximum retransmission time MRD Maximum retransmission duration RAND Randomization factor Specific values for each of these parameters relevant to the various messages are given in the subsections of Section 18.2, using values defined in Table 1 in Section 7.6.",
            "Adjusted": "The client retransmission behavior is controlled and described by the following variables: RT (Retransmission timeout), IRT (Initial retransmission time), MRC (Maximum retransmission count), MRT (Maximum retransmission time), MRD (Maximum retransmission duration), and RAND (Randomization factor). Specific values for each of these parameters relevant to the various messages are given in the subsections of Section 18.2, using values defined in Table 1 in Section 7.6."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The algorithm for RAND is common across all message transmissions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "With each message transmission or retransmission, the client sets RT according to the rules given below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If RT expires before the message exchange terminates, the client recomputes RT and retransmits the message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each of the computations of a new RT includes a randomization factor (RAND), which is a random number chosen with a uniform distribution between -0.1 and +0.1.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The randomization factor is included to minimize synchronization of messages transmitted by DHCP clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The algorithm for choosing a random number does not need to be cryptographically sound.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The algorithm SHOULD produce a different sequence of random numbers from each invocation of the DHCP client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "RT for the first message transmission is based on IRT: RT = IRT + RAND*IRT RT for each subsequent message transmission is based on the previous value of RT: RT = 2*RTprev + RAND*RTprev MRT specifies an upper bound on the value of RT (disregarding the randomization added by the use of RAND).",
            "Adjusted": "RT for the first message transmission is based on IRT: RT = IRT + RAND * IRT. RT for each subsequent message transmission is based on the previous value of RT: RT = 2 * RTprev + RAND * RTprev. MRT specifies an upper bound on the value of RT (disregarding the randomization added by the use of RAND)."
        },
